Exercise 1.2

Split the data set into a training set and a test set.

train = sample(nrow(Carseats), size = 300)

Exercise 1.3

Fit a normal regression tree to the training set. Plot the tree, and interpret the results. What test MSE do you obtain? - MSE: 4.310263 (varies depending upon your sample)

tree_carseats = tree(formula = Sales ~ ., data=Carseats, subset=train)
{plot(tree_carseats)
text(tree_carseats)

tree_carseats_prediction = predict(tree_carseats, Carseats[-train, ])
MSE_tree = mean((Carseats[-train, ]$Sales - tree_carseats_prediction)^2)}

Exercise 1.4

Cross-validation in order to determine the optimal level of tree complexity. Does pruning the tree improve the test MSE?

?cv.tree
cv_tree = cv.tree(tree(Sales ~ ., data=Carseats), K=10)
plot(cv_tree)

## A size of six appears to be the best option.

tree_pruned = prune.tree(tree(Sales ~ ., data=Carseats, subset=train), best = 6)

pruned_tree_prediction = predict(tree_pruned, Carseats[-train, ])
MSE_pruned = mean((Carseats[-train, ]$Sales - pruned_tree_prediction)^2)

Exercise 1.5

Use the bagging approach in order to analyze this data. What test MSE do you obtain? Use the importance() function to determine which variables are most important.

# Check the number of columns, we need columns - 1 for the number of features.
ncol(Carseats)
## [1] 11
# Create a bagging model using the randomForest library.
bagging_carseats = randomForest(Sales ~., data=Carseats, subset=train, mtry=(ncol(Carseats) - 1), ntree=500)

# Make a prediction and compute MSE.
bagging_prediction = predict(bagging_carseats, Carseats[-train, ])
mean((Carseats[-train, ]$Sales - bagging_prediction)^2)
## [1] 2.512292
# Find the most important variables
importance(bagging_carseats)
##             IncNodePurity
## CompPrice      225.487637
## Income         106.534419
## Advertising    188.811121
## Population      96.178401
## Price          630.990891
## ShelveLoc      725.277252
## Age            246.514599
## Education       62.257975
## Urban            9.841754
## US              11.368156
varImpPlot(bagging_carseats)

Exercise 1.6

Use the random forest algorithm to build a model. What test MSE do you obtain? Use the importance() function to determine which variables are most important.

forest_carseats = randomForest(Sales ~., data=Carseats, subset=train, mtry=sqrt(ncol(Carseats)), ntree=500)

forest_prediction = predict(forest_carseats, Carseats[-train, ])
mean((Carseats[-train,]$Sales - forest_prediction)^2)
## [1] 3.042799
